    Let <fr:tex>(Y,N,\beta )</fr:tex> satisfy <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.star"
href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.star.xml"
taxon="Property"
number="*"></fr:ref> above.

    
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(i) &quot;">
        Up to unique isomorphism, there exists exactly one <fr:tex>s</fr:tex>-split <fr:tex>(n+1)</fr:tex>-truncated topological space <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> augmented over <fr:tex>S</fr:tex> such that <fr:tex>\alpha (X)\simeq (Y,N,\beta )</fr:tex>.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(ii) &quot;">
        It is equivalent to give either <fr:tex>f\colon  X\to  Z</fr:tex> or:

        
 <html:ol>
          
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
            a morphism <fr:tex>f'\colon  Y\to \operatorname {sq}_n(Z)</fr:tex>; and
          </html:li>

          
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
            a morphism <fr:tex>f''\colon  N\to  Z_{n+1}</fr:tex>, such that the diagram
            <fr:tex
display="block">               \begin {CD}                 N @&gt;\beta &gt;&gt; (\operatorname {cosq} Y)_{n+1}               \\@V{f''}VV @VV{f'}V               \\Z_{n+1} @&gt;&gt;&gt; (\operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_n Z)_{n+1}               \end {CD}             </fr:tex>
            commutes.
          </html:li>

        </html:ol>

      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
  
    
